elements.content: The reaction of N,N′-dimethylene-2,2′-biimidazole (L) with various copper salts gives eight complexes that were characterized structurally in the solid state. This showed that the ligand can effectively bridge two copper atoms in close proximity similarly to the well-known bridging carboxylate motif. In reaction with copper(II), this gives a dimer (acetate, 1) or quadruple helicate (perchlorate, 2). Extention to copper(I) with a coordinating counterion gives a one-dimensional polymer (iodide, 3), while reaction with noncoordinating counterion gives M2L3 triple helicate motifs. These helicates were found to form chiral solvate-containing pockets surrounding benzene when combined with a three-fold symmetric anion (BF4 –, ClO4 – and NO3 –, 4, 5, and 6, respectively) or an achiral complex with only acetonitrile (ClO4 –, 7). While the pocket could accommodate fluorobenzene (BF4 –, 8), more highly substituted benzenes do not allow its formation.

Often, by simply mixing together the components, self-assembly processes lead to high yields of the resulting species, with the functionality of the product species derived from the combinations of metal and ligand. Ligands able to bridge metals in close vicinity are of considerable interest as the strong metal–metal interactions supported are known to encourage magnetic and electronic activity. Introduction

Metallosupramolecular chemistry uses the combination of bridging organic ligands and metal atoms for the construction of both discrete and 1-, 2-, or 3-D polymeric assemblies. Often, by simply mixing together the components, self-assembly processes lead to high yields of the resulting species, with the functionality of the product species derived from the combinations of metal and ligand. Ligands able to bridge metals in close vicinity are of considerable interest as the strong metal-metal interactions supported are known to encourage magnetic and electronic activity. The principal requirement for such ligands is that they have donor atoms that are sufficiently close with binding modes oriented in a direction that will allow bridging of metals in close proximity. The most commonly used donor group of this type is the carboxylate, which has been shown to bridge metal atoms on numerous occasions, for example, in the formation of copper paddlewheel complexes, which have been shown to have strong magnetic coupling between carboxylate bridged metal atoms. The small clusters produced are also commonly used as nodes for the production of simple coordination polymers and those with persistent porosity (metal-organic frameworks).

elements.content: We have an ongoing interest in nitrogen based heterocyclic ligands and their potential as a platform for the formation of supramolecular complexes with weakly coordinated metals such as silver and copper(I). We investigated N,N′-dimethylene-2,2′-biimidazole (L) (Figure a) as an aromatic heterocyclic structural analogue of carboxylate ligands and showed that its ability to bridge two silver atoms in close proximity was controlled by the anions involved. Here, the backbone is able to maintain almost coplanarity of the biheterocycle while it allows some twisting, and this restricts potential chelation by maintaining a narrow chelating angle (∼40°, cf ≈ 60° for 2,2′-bipyridine). In the present study, we decided to extend our use of this ligand to investigate the potential for L to bridge copper(II) and copper(I) in a manner similar to carboxylate ligands (Figure b). We hoped that using a heterocylic donor system would stabilize the formation of copper(I) complexes as only few examples of structurally characterized copper(I)–carboxylates exist. Compared to the wealth of copper(II)–carboxylate paddlewheels, there are few examples of N,N′-disubstituted 2,2′-biimidazole complexes with copper. Of these, the most common ligand used is N,N′-dimethyl-2,2′-biimidazole, and with copper(I) and copper(II), the free rotation about the inter-ring bond gives increased metal–metal separation.

Data were collected at 120(1) K on a Bruker APEXII area detector using graphite monochromised Mo Kα (γ = 0.71073 Å) radiation for structures 1–6 and on an Agilent Atlas area detector using microfocus graphite monochromised Cu Kα (γ = 1.5418 Å) for structures 7, 8, S1, and S2. Space groups were determined from systematic absences and checked for higher symmetry. Structures were solved by direct methods using SHELXS and refined with full-matrix least-squares on F 2 using SHELXL-97. All nonhydrogen atoms were refined anisotropically unless specified otherwise. Hydrogen atoms were included at geometrically estimated positions and refined with a riding model. Initially we decided to investigate L in a direct comparison with acetate as a ligand for copper(II). The reaction of L with copper(II) acetate in a 1:2 ligand-to-metal ratio gave blue, plate-shaped crystals of Cu2 L 2(OAc)4. These crystallized in the triclinic space group P1̅ with half of a Cu2 L 2(OAc)4 unit present in the asymmetric unit (along with one solvate molecule of acetonitrile), as shown in Figure . Here, two molecules of L bridge two copper atoms convergently, with the remaining coordination sites made up by two acetate anions bridging the copper atoms through a bifurcated oxygen atom and two additional capping acetate anions, a structure similar to that observed in the copper(II) acetate complex of N-methyl imidazole. This gives the copper(II) ions an overall square pyramidal geometry (N–Cu–N = 175.6(1)°, O–Cu–O = 82.1(1)°, 96.8(1)° and 178.8(1)°, N–Cu–O range from 88.8(1)° to 92.3(1)°, τ5 = 0.05), with a Cu···Cu distance of 3.167(1) Å, which is significantly longer than the intermetallic distance observed in the copper acetate paddle wheel (2.611 Å). The Cu···N distances (2.027(3) Å and 2.029(3) Å) and the Cu···O distances (bridging acetate Cu···O = 1.944(3) Å and 2.247(3) Å, capping acetate Cu···O = 1.937(3) Å) are within the range expected for coordinating nitrogenous heterocycles and acetate ligands, respectively. The two imidazole rings are only slightly twisted (plane–plane angle 10.6(2)°) relative to each other with the torsion angle (N–C–C–N) of the ethyl backbone angle of 47.6(5)°.

elements.content: The 1:1 reaction of L with Cu(ClO4)2 gave complex 2 with crystals suitable for X-ray crystallography obtained in 25% yield from the slow diffusion of benzene into the acetonitrile reaction mixture. Complex 2 crystallizes in the monoclinic space group P2/c, with four ligands bridging two copper atoms in a distinctive Cu2 L 4 quadruple helix, as shown in Figure . The copper atoms have square-based pyramidal coordination geometry, with the caps of the helix formed by coordinated perchlorate counterions. This dinuclear quadruple helicate motif, although only occasionally observed in metallosupramolecular chemistry, can be formed using monodentate ligands and either square-planar metals such as palladium or square-based pyramidal metals such as copper(II), for example, with N,N′-dimethylene-2,2′-biimidazoline. The asymmetric unit of 2 contains two cystallographically distinct Cu2 L 4 units with the copper atoms separated by 2.956(1) Å and 2.945(1) Å, Cu···N bonds ranging from 1.995(3) Å to 2.014(4) Å, and the capping Cu···O bonds of 2.284(5) Å and 2.312(4) Å.

elements.content: The ability of L to convergently bridge two copper(II) atoms prompted us to investigate the coordination ability of L with copper(I). Copper(I) ions have a somewhat more defined coordination geometry preference than silver(I) ions; copper(I) ions usually prefer a tetrahedral geometry as opposed to the promiscuous nature of the silver(I) ion, which can have coordination numbers ranging from 2–9. We chose to react L initially with CuI since, despite the large number of complexes with heterocyclic nitrogen atoms, there remain no structurally characterized coordination complexes of carboxylate ligands with copper(I) iodide, presumably due to their inherent instability. Thus, reaction of CuI with L in acetonitrile gave 3 as small colorless needles suitable for X-ray diffraction. Complex 3 crystallizes in the monoclinic space group P21/c with one molecule of L, two copper atoms, and two iodide anions present in the asymmetric unit. Complex 3 has a one-dimensional polymeric structure that propagates along the c-axis of the unit cell, with molecules of L convergently bridging two copper atoms at a distance of Cu···Cu = 2.640(1) Å, as shown in Figure , panel a, a separation similar to that found in other copper–iodide complexes. The Cu···N distances are comparable to the previous complexes (2.001(2) Å and 2.010(2) Å) as is the twist in the imidazole rings of L (8.1(1)°). Each copper atom is also bound to three iodide ions (Cu···I range from 2.637(1) Å to 2.775(1) Å) to give the copper atom a slightly distorted tetrahedral geometry (angles around the copper center range from 105.5(1)° to 115.8(1)°). Each iodide ion bridges three copper atoms to form a copper–iodide wire framework, with the wires insulated by molecules of L on alternating sides along each side of the polymer, as shown in Figure , panel b. The separation between the copper atoms bridged by iodide atoms (Cu···Cu = 2.8129(5) Å) illustrates the ability of L to support short metal–metal separation distances.

elements.content: We next reacted L with Cu(CH3CN)4BF4 in hot acetonitrile to form complex 4, which was cooled and then subjected to slow diffusion of benzene. Overnight, large, colorless cube-shaped crystals suitable for X-ray crystallography were formed in 47% yield from the reaction mixture. Intriguingly, 4 crystallizes in the chiral, cubic space group P4332 as a Cu2 L 3 dinuclear triple helicate (shown in Figure ), a subunit almost identical to that observed by Widilika et al., although this did not form in a chiral space group. The helical subunit lies across the three-fold and two-fold axes. Again, a molecule of L convergently bridges both copper atoms, with a intermetallic distance of 2.714(1) Å, and the copper atoms have a slightly distorted trigonal planar geometry (N–Cu–N angle = 118.7(1)°), with all Cu···N distances = 1.983(2) Å. The imidazole rings of the molecule of L in complex 4 are twisted out of plane relative to each other by 12.4(2)°, and the torsion angle of the ethyl bridging backbone (N–C–C–N) is 51.4(5)°. The ethyl backbones of all three molecules of L that make up the Cu2 L 3 triple helicate twist in the same direction, and this common directionality imparts a small pitch to the dinuclear triple helicate (7.8(1)°).

elements.content: Given the similarity of the symmetry of the anion (principal three-fold axis) in complex 4, with the symmetry shown by the complex and solvate pocket, we decided to react L with copper(I) salts of similar anions. Thus, the reaction of L with Cu(CH3CN)4ClO4 in acetonitrile gave complex 5, and that with Cu(PPh3)2NO3 in acetonitrile gave complex 6, both isolated upon diffusion of benzene into the reaction mixture as crystals suitable for single crystal structure analysis. Both complexes 5 and 6 form in the chiral cubic space groups P4132 and P4332 (an enantiomorphous pair), respectively, with structures almost identical to 4 above (see ). Despite the different handedness of the helix in these structures, the complexes are formed from achiral starting materials, and hence, the bulk is a racemic mixture of crystals (as determined by a random selection of 10 crystals of each sample). Complexes 5 and 6 have structural parameters in line with their similarity to complex 4, Cu···Cu distances 2.726(1) Å and 2.707(1) Å, and Cu···N distances 1.982(3) Å and 1.976(2) Å, respectively, and overall trigonal planarity of the copper atoms. The twisting in the imidazole rings of L in each complex (13.0(2)° and 12.3(1)°, respectively) and torsion angle of the ethyl backbone (N–C–C–N angle 49.9(5)° and 51.6(6)°, respectively) impart only slight helical pitch as defined by the angles subtended by each ligand about the helical axis (8.2(2)° and 8.1(1)°, for complexes 5 and 6, respectively). As in complex 4, the anions of 5 and 6 are disordered and held in place by weak interactions with the ethyl backbone hydrogen atoms.

elements.content: Given the similarity of the structures of formed 4–6, we endeavored to determine the solution structures of these complexes. Thus, NMR spectra were collected from solutions of all three complexes redisolved in acetonitrile. All three complexes display identical NMR spectra, which show one series of ligand peaks shifted downfield relative to uncoordinated L (coordination induced shift ∼0.2 ppm). A peak in the NMR spectrum is also observed for the benzene molecule present in the crystal structure, with an integral that corresponds to a single benzene molecule for each complex. This peak is not shifted compared to solvent benzene (in CD3CN), and hence, we do not believe that the pocket remains intact in solution. The self-assembly of the helical subunit was observed by the gradual addition of a CD3CN solution of Cu(CH3CN)4BF4 into a CD3CN solution of L (). The two imidazole peaks of uncoordinated L coalesce into a single broad peak after the addition of one aliquot of tetrakis acetonitrile salt and only separate into two imidazole peaks of coordinated L once an excess of copper(I) salt is added. An NMR spectrum was retaken of the titration sample after 1 h, but the peaks had not separated further. The coalescence of peaks indicates that the formation of the dinuclear triple helicate is dynamic in solution. The titration was repeated with a drop of benzene added to the initial solution of L, to determine if this affects the self-assembly process, but the coalescence of peaks was identical to that observed in CD3CN only. The destruction of the pockets was also confirmed by ESMS of dissolved crystals of complexes 4–6, which gave only peaks corresponding to Cu2 L 3 2+ or its fragmentation products. The stability of the complex 4 in the solid state was monitored by TGA, with gradual solvent loss occurring above 175 °C (see ).

elements.content: The requirement for diffusion of solvents with symmetry similar to benzene was investigated by diffusion of different solvents into solutions of Cu(CH3CN)4X (X = ClO4 and BF4). Hexafluorobenzene, which matches the D6h symmetry and is only slightly larger than benzene, was used as the initial diffusion solvent. Crystals were isolated of the complex with perchlorate as a counterion, although analysis of these showed no hexafluorobenzene in the structure, only the presence of acetonitrile solvate (7). The complex crystallized in the achiral low symmetry triclinic space group P1̅ with one intact Cu2 L 3 helical unit, two perchlorate anions, and one molecule of acetonitrile present in the asymmetric unit. The Cu2 L 3 helical subunit is shown in Figure , panel a, and the solvate encapsulating pocket is now absent from the structure. The copper atoms have distorted trigonal planar geometry (N–Cu–N angles range from 97.0(1)° to 139.7(1)°); the Cu···Cu distances (2.684(1) Å) and Cu···N distances (ranging from 1.934(2) Å to 2.061(2) Å) along with the twisting of the imidazole rings of 7 (7.6(1)°, 9.5(1)°, and 14.6(1)°) and the torsion angles of the ethyl backbone (N–C–C–N range from 46.0(2)° to 49.8(2)°) are comparable to complexes 4–6. elements.content: In the case of 7, the hexafluorobenzene molecule is either too large or its C–F edge-to-face π–π interactions too weak to allow the formation of the pocket. A larger less electron deficient molecule (mesitylene, D3h symmetry) was also used for vapor diffusion into solutions of Cu(CH3CN)4X (X = ClO4 and BF4) and L, but no crystals suitable for single crystal X-ray diffraction or analysis were obtained. Fluorobenzene is somewhat smaller than hexafluorobenzene and mesitylene, although it has reduced C2v symmetry, and crystals suitable for X-ray diffraction were obtained from its diffusion into the reaction mixture of L and Cu(CH3CN)4BF4 (8). The complex formed crystallized in the cubic chiral space group P4132 and is isostrucural with complex 4, with a similar coordination geometry (Cu···N distances = 1.979(3) Å; N–Cu–N angle = 118.8(1)°) and the structural features of the triple helicate (intermetallic distance = 2.706(2) Å; helicate twist = 6.8(1)°). Because of the high symmetry of the complex, the fluorine atom of fluorobenzene is disordered over three positions, with the atom oriented toward the aperture’s of the pocket, as shown in Figure . Clearly the slightly increased size of fluorobenzene has not affected the ability of the helicates to arrange into the observed pocket, with the distribution of the disordered fluorine atoms matching the observed symmetry of the complex. This arrangement also allows the formation of stronger C–H edge-to-face π–π interactions between the hydrogen atoms of fluorobenzene and the imidazole rings (edge-to-centroid distance 3.716(8) Å).

Conclusions

In the course of this study, we have shown the ability of N,N'-dimethylene-2,2'-biimidazole to effectively bridge copper(II) atoms in close proximity and form a M2 L 2 complex with acetate and a dinuclear quadruple helicate with the less coordinating perchlorate anion. Unlike carboxylates, in combination with copper(I) iodide, N,N'-dimethylene-2,2'-biimidazole was able to bridge metal atoms and form a one-dimensional polymer. Using noncoordinating counterions, this bridging mode allows the formation of M2 L 3 triple helicates in the solution and solid state. We have further been able to demonstrate these helicates form a pocket around suitable aromatic guests. This was shown to be a feature of the solid-state structures and to require a suitably small aromatic guest (benzene or fluorobenzene) and an anion with principal three-fold axis (BF4 -, ClO4 -, or NO3 -). These pockets are maintained by edge-to-face interactions between the guest molecules and the aromatic system of the ligand molecules.
